In [56]:
# Pivot the DataFrame to have 'short_name' as columns and 'price' as values
pivot_df = df.pivot(index='timestamp', columns='short_name', values='price')
pivot_df.head()

# Calculate daily returns
returns = pivot_df.pct_change().dropna()
returns.tail()

# Calculate correlation matrix with pearson method (standard correlation coefficient)
correlation_matrix = returns.corr()
correlation_matrix.head()


# Plot a heatmap of the correlation matrix
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
sns.heatmap(correlation_matrix, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', vmin=-1, vmax=1)
plt.title('Correlation Matrix of BIST30 Stock Returns')
plt.show()

# Identify highly correlated pairs
threshold = 0.75  # Threshold can be adjusted based on preference
highly_correlated_pairs = []
for i in range(len(correlation_matrix.columns)):
    for j in range(i + 1, len(correlation_matrix.columns)):
        if abs(correlation_matrix.iloc[i, j]) > threshold:
            pair = (correlation_matrix.columns[i], correlation_matrix.columns[j])
            highly_correlated_pairs.append(pair)

print('Highly correlated pairs:')
for pair in highly_correlated_pairs:
    print(pair)

# Perform linear regression using ordinary least squares
X = sm.add_constant(df_train_AK_GA[stockA])

model1 = sm.OLS(df_train_AK_GA[stockB], X).fit()

# Print regression summary
print(f"Linear Regression Results for {stockA} and {stockB}:")
print(model1.summary())

# Plot the regression line
plt.scatter(df_train_AK_GA[stockA], df_train_AK_GA[stockB], label='Actual Prices')
plt.plot(df_train_AK_GA[stockA], model1.predict(X), color='red', label='Regression Line')
plt.xlabel(f'Price of {stockA}')
plt.ylabel(f'Price of {stockB}')
plt.title(f'Linear Regression: {stockA} vs. {stockB}')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

In [76]:
# Calculate residuals
residuals = model1.resid

# Calculate standard deviation of residuals
residual_std_dev = residuals.std()

# Establish control limits (e.g., 2 times the standard deviation)
control_limit = 2 * residual_std_dev

df_test_AK_GA = df_test[df_test['short_name'].isin([stockA, stockB])].pivot(index='timestamp', columns='short_name', values='price')
df_test_AK_GA['Predicted value of GARAN'] = 1.412*df_test_AK_GA['AKBNK'] + 2.394
df_test_AK_GA['Residual Value'] = df_test_AK_GA['Predicted value of GARAN'] - df_test_AK_GA['GARAN']

df_test_AK_GA['LCL'] = -control_limit
df_test_AK_GA['UCL'] = control_limit

# Generate trading signals based on control chart
df_test_AK_GA['Signal'] = 0  # 0 indicates no signal


df_test_AK_GA.loc[df_test_AK_GA['Residual Value'] > control_limit, 'Signal'] = -1  # -1 indicates short signal
df_test_AK_GA.loc[df_test_AK_GA['Residual Value'] < -control_limit, 'Signal'] = 1  # 1 indicates long signal

df_test_AK_GA.head()

In [77]:
# Simulate trading
initial_capital = 100000  # Set your initial trading capital
capital = initial_capital
position = 0  # 0 indicates no position

for i in range(1, len(df_test_AK_GA)):
    if df_test_AK_GA['Signal'].iloc[i] == 1 and position == 0:  # Long signal
        position = capital / df_test_AK_GA[stockA].iloc[i]  # Invest all capital in stockA
        capital = 0
    elif df_test_AK_GA['Signal'].iloc[i] == -1 and position > 0:  # Short signal and there is a long position
        capital = position * df_test_AK_GA[stockB].iloc[i]  # Sell stockB and convert to capital
        position = 0

# Calculate final capital
final_capital = capital + position * df_test_AK_GA[stockA].iloc[-1]

print(f"Trading simulation results for {stockA} and {stockB}:")
print(f"Initial Capital: {initial_capital}")
print(f"Final Capital: {final_capital}")
print(f"Total Return: {(final_capital - initial_capital) / initial_capital * 100:.2f}%")
print("------------")

Trading simulation results for AKBNK and GARAN:
Initial Capital: 100000
Final Capital: 191813.60201511334
Total Return: 91.81%
